<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

    <!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
        <handout margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="Week11Fri">
            <title>Friday Week 11 - Power Functions</title>
<page>
        <objectives>
          <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Define and recognize power functions.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find formulas for power functions from points on the graph.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Identify general graph features based on the coefficient and exponent in power functions.
                </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </objectives>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    Power functions are one more basic class of functions that involves two parameters. They are relatively simple to work with algebraically, but in contrast to other families, they can display a multitude of graphical behaviors.
                </p>
            </introduction>



<definition><title>Power Function</title>


    <statement>
        <p workspace="2in">
           A <term>power function</term> is one of the form...
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Decide if each of the following are power functions. For those that are power functions, identify the coefficient and exponent. Also, give a rough sketch of the graph if you can.
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p workspace="1in">
                    <m>f(x) = 12x^6</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p workspace="1in">
                    <m>g(x) = \frac{2}{x^3}</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p workspace="1in">
                    <m>h(x) = x\sqrt{x}</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p workspace="1in">
                    <m>k(x) = x^3 + 3x + 7</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </statement>

</example>

</page>
<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Finding Formulas</title>
<p>
    
</p>
<p workspace="3in">
    Find a formula for a power function <m>y=f(x)</m> such that <m>f(2) = 12</m> and <m>f(3) = 16</m>.
</p>

</paragraphs>   

<paragraphs>
    <title>Graphs of Positive Integer Powers</title>
    <p>
        Match the following functions to its graph: <m>y = x^2</m>, <m>y = x^3</m>, <m>y = x^4</m>, <m>y = x^5</m>.
    </p>
        <sidebyside>
    <image>
<prefigure label="poseven" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="10">
  <definition>f(x)=x^2</definition>
<definition>g(x)=x^4</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(-3,-3,3,3)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
    <graph function="f"/>
    <graph function="g" stroke="green"/>
  </coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image> 
    <image>
<prefigure label="posodd" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="10">
  <definition>f(x)=x^3</definition>
  <definition>g(x)=x^5</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(-3,-3,3,3)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
    <graph function="f"/>
    <graph function="g" stroke="green"/>
  </coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image> 
    </sidebyside>
</paragraphs>


</page>

<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Graphs of Negative Integer Powers</title>
    <p>
        Match the following functions to its graph: <m>y = x^{-2}</m>, <m>y = x^{-3}</m>, <m>y = x^{-4}</m>, <m>y = x^{-5}</m>.
    </p>
        <sidebyside>
    <image>
<prefigure label="negeven" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="10">
  <definition>f(x)=x^(-2)</definition>
    <definition>g(x)=x^(-4)</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(-3,-3,3,3)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
    <graph function="f"/>
    <graph function="g" stroke="green"/>
  </coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image> 
    <image>
<prefigure label="neqodd" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="10">
  <definition>f(x)=x^(-3)</definition>
    <definition>g(x)=x^(-5)</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(-3,-3,3,3)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
    <graph function="f"/>
    <graph function="g" stroke="green"/>
  </coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image> 
    </sidebyside>
</paragraphs>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Graphs of Positive Fractional Powers</title>
    <p>
        Match the following functions to its graph: <m>y = x^{1/2}</m>, <m>y = x^{1/3}</m>, <m>y = x^{1/4}</m>, <m>y = x^{1/5}</m>.
    </p>
    <image>
<prefigure label="frac" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(400,400)" margins="(100,5,100,5)">
  <definition>f(x)=sqrt(x)</definition>
  <definition>g(x)=exp(ln(x)/3)</definition>
  <definition>h(x)=sqrt(sqrt(x))</definition>
  <definition>k(x)=exp(ln(x)/5)</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(0,0,2,2)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
    <graph function="f"/>
    <graph function="g" stroke="black"/>
    <graph function="h" stroke="green"/>
    <graph function="k" stroke="red"/>
  </coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image> 
</paragraphs>



</page>

<page>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Summary of Behavior Near Zero or <m>\pm\infty</m></title>
        <p></p>
        <p>
            Describe how <m>f(x) = kx^p</m> behaves as <m>x\to\pm\infty</m>, <m>x\to 0^{+}</m>, or <m>x\to 0^{-}</m>, depending on the given combinations of <m>k</m> and <m>p</m> (sketch a graph for each).
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>k&gt; 0</m> and <m>p</m> is positive and even.
                </p>
                <p workspace="2in">
                    As <m>x\to\pm \infty</m>, <m>y\to</m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>k&gt; 0</m> and <m>p</m> is negative and even.
                </p>
                <p>
                    As <m>x\to\pm \infty</m>, <m>y\to</m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
                <p workspace="2in">
                    As <m>x\to\pm 0</m>, <m>y\to</m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>k&gt; 0</m> and <m>p</m> is positive and odd.
                </p>
                <p>
                    As <m>x\to \infty</m>, <m>y\to</m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
                <p workspace="2in">
                    As <m>x\to -\infty</m>, <m>y\to</m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>k&gt; 0</m> and <m>p</m> is negative and odd.
                </p>
                <p>
                    As <m>x\to\pm \infty</m>, <m>y\to</m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
                <p>
                    As <m>x\to 0^{+}</m>, <m>y\to</m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
                <p workspace="2in">
                   As <m>x\to 0^{-}</m>, <m>y\to</m><fillin characters="5" />
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>


    </paragraphs>


</page>
        

